%T A393551 1107,9318,72170,299982,1,30,280,3658,41749,437971,4843626
%N A393551 T(n,k) is the number of distinct enforceable unique-solution shadings in an n X k Hitori puzzle up to rotation and reflection, read by rows.
%C A393551 A shading (set of black cells) is "enforceable" in an n X k Hitori puzzle if there exists at least one initial number placement such that the puzzle has a unique solution and that solution shades exactly those cells black.
%C A393551 Equivalently: the black cells form an independent set in the grid graph (no two share an edge), the white cells form exactly one 4-connected component, the all-white pattern is excluded, and the pattern can be the unique solution of some valid numbered Hitori instance.
%C A393551 For square boards (n = k) the count is up to the dihedral group D4 (rotations and reflections); that is, symmetric variants are counted once using a canonical representative (e.g. lexicographically smallest bitstring under the 8 transformations).
%C A393551 For rectangular boards (m < n), the count is up to reflection symmetry: horizontally symmetric and vertically symmetric patterns are counted as 1 (canonical under horizontal and vertical flips, equivalent to the Klein four-group).
%H A393551 Douglas Boffey, <a href="/A393551/a393551.cc.txt">Code used to generate dataset</a>
%H A393551 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hitori">Hitori</a>.
